    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n1. Add a variable called `loves_pizza` that stores a boolean value (`True` or `False`).\r\n2. Uncomment the **first `print()` line** by removing the hash `#`. What do you think will happen when you click \"Run\"?\r\n3. Run the code and observe the error message. What is causing this error?\r\n4. Comment out the **first `print()` line** by using the `#`. Then, uncomment the **second `print()` line**.\r\n5. Run the code and consider:\r\n    * *How did adding `str()` fix the error?* \r\n    * *What does it do to the Boolean variable?*\r\n    \r\n::: details [**Exploring Comments `#`**]\r\n`#` in Python: The `#` symbol is used to write a comment, which is a note to yourself or others reading your code. Python ignores anything after the # on that line, so it's not run as code.\r\n\r\n**Comment out:** This means you're adding a `#` in front of a line of code so it won’t run. It’s like temporarily turning it off.\r\n\r\n**Uncomment:** This means you're removing the `#` so that the line of code will run again.\r\n:::\r\n\r\n::: details [**🔎 Show me how**]\r\nTo enlarge the code drag out the side bar of the instruction box.\r\n![](https://images.code.org/d28f10f162adb144dd5f316ccc90faac-image-1743090929464.png)\r\n:::\r\n\r\n"
